00:49:57.550 --> 00:50:01.270
So we always had a higher cash
position than most people.

00:50:01.270 --> 00:50:04.040
But in a time when
there are great values,

00:50:04.040 --> 00:50:05.710
we have a little less cash.

00:50:05.710 --> 00:50:09.590
Today, I feel one of the
best cash items is gold.

00:50:09.590 --> 00:50:11.790
And so we don't
have as much cash,

00:50:11.790 --> 00:50:14.580
but we do have a lot
more in the gold market.

00:50:14.580 --> 00:50:16.530
So the answer is cash.

00:50:16.530 --> 00:50:18.670
Even if cash doesn't
make any money,

00:50:18.670 --> 00:50:20.680
it's better than losing money.

00:50:20.680 --> 00:50:22.490
So you have to be patient.

00:50:22.490 --> 00:50:27.530
And that's one of the principles
you learn is patient pays off.

00:50:27.530 --> 00:50:32.420
One thing I can tell you of
being 48 years in the business,

00:50:32.420 --> 00:50:35.252
you will always find
values if you're patient.

00:50:35.252 --> 00:50:36.960
You might have to wait
a year and a half.

00:50:36.960 --> 00:50:38.690
You might have to
wait two years.

00:50:38.690 --> 00:50:41.480
But my God, what I went
through writing this thing down

00:50:41.480 --> 00:50:45.720
for six years, I wouldn't wish
that on the worst human being.

00:50:45.720 --> 00:50:49.090
That's a terrible thing to do
to come to the office every day

00:50:49.090 --> 00:50:50.150
and just get beat up.

00:50:50.150 --> 00:50:51.780
It's just like a torture.

00:50:51.780 --> 00:50:55.810
So if you're not sure, if you
don't have a great opportunity,

00:50:55.810 --> 00:50:58.990
it's better to take no
interest than it looks.

00:50:58.990 --> 00:51:02.430
AUDIENCE: I'm just
curious about Apple.

00:51:02.430 --> 00:51:04.420
It's, like, the world's
biggest company.

00:51:04.420 --> 00:51:06.450
The P/E is probably
at, like, 10.

00:51:06.450 --> 00:51:11.980
[INAUDIBLE] 7 P/E. And
meanwhile, all the other tech

00:51:11.980 --> 00:51:14.960
companies are way
higher, like Microsoft.

00:51:14.960 --> 00:51:17.795
SPEAKER: So the
question is about Apple.

00:51:17.795 --> 00:51:19.600
It's a low P/E, about 10.

00:51:19.600 --> 00:51:22.210
And they have a lot of cash
on their balance sheet.

00:51:22.210 --> 00:51:25.985
So if you take the cash out,
it's even lower P/E in effect.

00:51:25.985 --> 00:51:28.110
How do you think about
that, because all other tech

00:51:28.110 --> 00:51:31.890
companies are selling at
more expensive prices?

00:51:31.890 --> 00:51:34.410
ARNOLD VAN DEN BERG: Well,
I think by all criteria,

00:51:34.410 --> 00:51:37.410
you would have a great value.

00:51:37.410 --> 00:51:39.300
The question that
I have-- and I'm

00:51:39.300 --> 00:51:42.390
sorry that I can't give you a
definitive answer, because we

00:51:42.390 --> 00:51:43.450
don't follow it.

00:51:43.450 --> 00:51:44.800
We're not in it.

00:51:44.800 --> 00:51:47.530
But the thing is,
from all standpoints,

00:51:47.530 --> 00:51:50.850
just from a cursory standpoint,
you're right about the cash.

00:51:50.850 --> 00:51:52.590
If you took it on,
it'd be cheaper.

00:51:52.590 --> 00:51:54.680
They've got all
this opportunity,

00:51:54.680 --> 00:51:58.010
they've got a lot of
money in the bank.

00:51:58.010 --> 00:52:00.490
But my question
is, what are they

00:52:00.490 --> 00:52:02.250
going to do for the future?

00:52:02.250 --> 00:52:04.340
That's the most important thing.

00:52:04.340 --> 00:52:07.420
And I'm not qualified to
answer that, because I'm not

00:52:07.420 --> 00:52:09.710
a technical person.

00:52:09.710 --> 00:52:12.090
But if I was looking
at the company,

00:52:12.090 --> 00:52:14.160
and we've looked at
it back and forth,

00:52:14.160 --> 00:52:16.450
the thing that I have
a big question mark

00:52:16.450 --> 00:52:19.920
is, what are they going
to do into the future?

00:52:19.920 --> 00:52:23.170
Because you can have a
low P/E. As long as you

00:52:23.170 --> 00:52:25.400
have less than 10
times cash flow,

00:52:25.400 --> 00:52:27.830
you get a 10% cash flow return.

00:52:27.830 --> 00:52:31.110
And so you could keep this
even if it didn't go up.

00:52:31.110 --> 00:52:34.210
If the price didn't go up,
the value keeps going up,

00:52:34.210 --> 00:52:35.630
and it pushes the price up.

00:52:35.630 --> 00:52:38.360
So I wouldn't fault
anybody for saying this

00:52:38.360 --> 00:52:40.180
is an extraordinary bargain.

00:52:40.180 --> 00:52:41.780
But the question I
have, and you would

00:52:41.780 --> 00:52:45.290
be able to answer it better than
I do, is what is the future?

00:52:45.290 --> 00:52:47.140
And I remember one of
my analysts came to me

00:52:47.140 --> 00:52:49.370
and he says, Arnold, we
ought to look at Apple.

00:52:49.370 --> 00:52:51.905
And it was the highest
capitalization in the market.

00:52:51.905 --> 00:52:54.590
And I said, you
know, Dale, I said,

00:52:54.590 --> 00:52:56.870
it's been my experience
when a company gets

00:52:56.870 --> 00:53:01.190
to be the biggest capitalization
in the history of the market,

00:53:01.190 --> 00:53:03.560
if you look at the
next five to 10 years,

00:53:03.560 --> 00:53:05.770
the performance
isn't all that great.

00:53:05.770 --> 00:53:09.180
Now that's not a
judgment on the company.

00:53:09.180 --> 00:53:14.720
But when it's so big, bigger
than anything around, what

00:53:14.720 --> 00:53:17.890
did they have to do to create
that growth to keep it going?

00:53:17.890 --> 00:53:19.440
So it's a very good question.

00:53:19.440 --> 00:53:21.480
I wish I could give
you the answer.

00:53:21.480 --> 00:53:24.960
If I could, I'd probably buy it.

00:53:24.960 --> 00:53:27.100
SPEAKER: So unfortunately,
we are out of time.

00:53:27.100 --> 00:53:29.330
But I hope there will
be time to continue

00:53:29.330 --> 00:53:31.480
this conversation outside.

00:53:31.480 --> 00:53:33.300
ARNOLD VAN DEN BERG: Oh, sure.

00:53:33.300 --> 00:53:35.860
SPEAKER: So thank you, everyone.

